---
layout: post
title: Validation of the Wilks Coefficient with Raw Powerlifting Scoreboards
---

Imagine a person weighting 100 kg and lifting 150 kg. Is this person stronger than another person lifting just 140kg with 70kg body weight? In the absolute numbers yes. But in respect to their body weights? It depends.


<p>
In the powerlifting world there exists something called the Wilks equation. With the Wilks equation you can estimate the Wilks points according to the body weight of a lifter, total weight lifted and gender. The total weight lifted is the sum of benchpress, squat and deadlift. The process of estimating the number of Wilks points is called the Wilks normalization. The Wilks normalization is used by many powerlifting federations. Sometimes it is also considered fair enough to be even used across the weight categories - to find the absolute winner of a powerlifting competition.
</p>
<p>
On the other hand, a lot of people are complaining about this score. In my humble opinion, mainly the heavier people consider the Wilks score unfair, because it allows somebody with a lower total weight lifted to beat them in a competition. 
</p>
<p>
Many alternatives to Wilks equation exist. Most common is the normalization of the lifted weight according to the body weight. If you ever heard: “You should deadlift at least 2 times your body weight!”, then you know what I am talking about. According to this normalization, if 70 kg lifter lifts 210 kg, then the 150 kg lifter should lift 450kg to be just equal. You can probably imagine why this normalization seems to be popular among the people with a lower body weight.
</p>
<p>
So it seems that every normalization has some supporters and also complainers. The question remains, is the Wilks normalization a fair way how to compare lifters (or ordinary guys) with different body weight? 
</p>


<h2>Issue of Wilks Validation</h2>
<p>
I found a lot of discussions about validity of Wilks normalization and also one scientific study <a href="http://europepmc.org/abstract/med/10613442">(Vanderburgh PM, Batterham AM. Validation of the Wilks powerlifting formula. Medicine and science in sports and exercise. 1999 Dec;31(12):1869-75.)</a>. Problem is that every validation what I have found uses only the world records as a sample of population. That would be (maybe) good idea if you want to compare world records in different weight categories. But <span class="emp">the Wilks normalization is used during various competitions for thousands of lifters, so it does not really make sense to optimize it according a few record holders</span>. For your better understanding of the issue I prepared the following figure of simplified situation. Later in this post, you will see that the reality is like this (but slightly less straightforward).
</p>

<div class="regular_caption">Simplified relation of body weight and total according to skill level</div>
<img class="half_image" src="/images/wilks1/lines_example.png" alt="Relation of body weight and total according to skill level"> 


<h2>Chosen Population Sample for the Wilks Validation</h2>
<p>
To find out what is the most fair way of the lifted weight normalization, I used a big sample of raw powerlifters.
<span class="emp">The raw powerlifting is closer to lifting heavy stuff in real life than the powerlifting with gear</span>, therefore I select only records from raw powerlifters for the validation sample.
This sample is obtained from USAPL federation scoreboards.
It contains records from all possible raw divisions and weight categories from events between 2012-2016. The sample distribution across divisions is in the following pie chart.
</p>
<div class="regular_caption">Distribution of lifters in divisions</div>
<img class="half_image" src="/images/wilks1/raw_pie_chart.png" alt="Divisions distribution in the sample of USAPL"> 
<p>
<span class="emp">This data-set contains records from 8091 men and 3028 women.</span>
Every man or woman has only one record in the data-set.
The data-set statistical attributes are displayed in the following table.
<ul>
    <li>The <span class="emp">mean</span> stands for arithmetic mean value.</li>
    <li>The <span class="emp">median</span> is median value (most common value).</li>
    <li>The <span class="emp">std</span> is standard deviation (how much the data vary).</li>
    <li>The <span class="emp">min</span> and the <span class="emp">max</span> are the minimal and maximal value.</li>
</ul>
</p>
<div class="regular_caption">Statistical attributes of the data-set</div>
