<h2>Wilks Coefficient and the Total Weight Lifted</h2>
<p>
Now it is time to answer the main question - <i>Is the Wilks normalization fair?</i>. Let's start with a figure.
</p>
<div class="regular_caption">Dependency of the total weight lifted on the body weight (all divisions)</div>
<img class="regular_image" src="/images/wilks1/wilks_total.png" alt="Dependency of total weight lifted on body weight"> 
<p>
Now, you can probably see the same things as I do. If not, see the following table containing correlations of the body weights and totals.
If you do not remember what is correlation coefficient:
<ul>
    <li>correlation coefficient close to 1.0 - the body weight is directly related to the total weight lifted</li>
    <li>correlation coefficient close to -1.0 - the body weight is indirectly related to the total weight lifted</li>
    <li>correlation coefficient close to 0 - the body weight is not related to the total weight lifted</li>
</ul>
The last note - almost every correlation has its p-value<0.05, only the women teen division has higher p-value for the body weight normalization, so there is only negligible chance that the found correlations are random.
</p>
<div class="regular_caption">Correlation coefficients of the body weight and the total weight lifted</div>
<table class="table table-stripped table-small">
<thead>
    <tr>
        <th>Gender</th>  
        <th>Division</th>
        <th>Athletes</th>
        <th>Lifted Weight</th>
        <th>Wilks Points</th>
        <th>Lifted / Body Weight</th>
    </tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Men</td><td></td><td>8091</td><td>0.585</td><td>0.188</td><td>-0.231</td></tr>
<tr><td>Men</td><td>Master</td><td>910</td><td>0.519</td><td>0.179</td><td>-0.232</td></tr>
<tr><td>Men</td><td>Open</td><td>3789</td><td>0.584</td><td>0.178</td><td>-0.286</td></tr>
<tr><td>Men</td><td>Teen</td><td>1587</td><td>0.566</td><td>0.116</td><td>-0.256</td></tr>
<tr><td>Men</td><td>Junior</td><td>1608</td><td>0.618</td><td>0.157</td><td>-0.297</td></tr>
<tr><td>Women</td><td></td><td>3028</td><td>0.501</td><td>0.029</td><td>-0.279</td></tr>
<tr><td>Women</td><td>Master</td><td>433</td><td>0.401</td><td>-0.146</td><td>-0.441</td></tr>
<tr><td>Women</td><td>Open</td><td>1702</td><td>0.522</td><td>0.053</td><td>-0.273</td></tr>
<tr><td>Women</td><td>Teen</td><td>315</td><td>0.533</td><td>0.061</td><td>-0.224</td></tr>
<tr><td>Women</td><td>Junior</td><td>506</td><td>0.535</td><td>0.055</td><td>-0.239</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>
Finally, here is the conclusion of the figure and the table:
<ul class="emp_result">
    <li>Heavier people really have bigger totals in general, thus a normalization is needed.</li>
    <li>The Wilks normalization seems slightly sub-optimal for men and almost optimal for women (as far as we can test with this sample).</li>
    <li>The Wilks normalization is more fair than normalization according to the body weight.</li>
    <li>It seems that lifters are less dependent on their body weight with increasing age in general (exception is teen men).</li>
</ul>
</p>


<h2>Wilks Coefficient and the Individual Lifts</h2>
<p>
Other minor question is, whether the Wilks coefficient can be used for the normalization of an individual lift.
Theoretically it should not, because it was designed according to the total weight lifted distribution.
In other words, every lift is specific and needs own way of normalization, therefore <span class="emp">one particular normalization cannot be universal for every kind of lift</span>.
No matter how obvious it is, a lot of people is still using the Wilks coefficient to compare lifters according to a single lift.
In their defense, they do not have too many other options, therefore I understand them.
</p>
<p>
Let's see, how big mistake one can do with the Wilks normalization usage for a single lift. See table of correlations below. Again, all correlations are significant (p<0.05).
</p>
<div class="regular_caption">Correlation coefficients of the body weight and the individual lifts</div>
<table class="table table-stripped table-small">
<thead>
    <tr>
        <th></th>    
        <th>Lifted Weight</th>
        <th>Wilks Points</th>
        <th>Lifted / Body Weight</th>
    </tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Men Deadlift</td><td>0.524</td><td>0.075</td><td>-0.331</td></tr>
<tr><td>Women Deadlift</td><td>0.493</td><td>-0.024</td><td>-0.333</td></tr>
<tr><td>Men Squat</td><td>0.568</td><td>0.218</td><td>-0.154</td></tr>
<tr><td>Women Squat</td><td>0.473</td><td>0.045</td><td>-0.231</td></tr>
<tr><td>Men Benchpress</td><td>0.568</td><td>0.243</td><td>-0.11</td></tr>
<tr><td>Women Benchpress</td><td>0.459</td><td>0.081</td><td>-0.174</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>
In the above table we can see some interesting points:
<ul class="emp_result">
    <li>Performance of men is more dependent on the body weight than performance of women.</li>
    <li>The Wilks normalization seems to work not too bad. The worst result for men is benchpress and the best result I calculated for women is deadlift.</li>
    <li>The Wilks normalization is more fair than the normalization according to the body weight, except the men squat and men benchpress</li>
</ul>
</p>

<h2>What is Good According to Wilks</h2>
<p>
You probably wonder, whether you are better than average according to the Wilks score.
The following table can give you a clue.
But do not fool yourself, this data-set consists of people with various age and lifting experience. If you compare yourself with the table values, there is no assurance that the output will be fair or relevant. 
</p>
